g Imagery in American Visual Culture -- tTalking Back -- t17. Differences at Play in the Fields of the Lord -- t18. American Samson: Biblical Reading and National Origins -- t19. Against Signifying: Psychosocial Needs and Natural Evil -- t20. Orality, Memory, and Power: Vedic Scriptures and Brahmanical Hegemony in India -- t21. Reading Places/Reading Scriptures -- t22. Taniwha and Serpent: A Trans-Tasman Riff -- t23. Scriptures Without Letters, Subversions of Pictography, Signifyin(g) Alphabetical Writing -- tTalking Back -- t24. In Hoc Signum Vincent: A Midrashist Replies -- t25. Powerful Words: The Social-intellectual Location of the International Signifying Scriptures Project -- t26. Racial and Colonial Politics of the Modern Object of Knowledge: Cautionary Notes on "Scripture" -- t27. Who Needs the Subaltern? -- tTalking Back -- tBibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistorically, religious scriptures are defined as holy texts that are considered to be beyond the abilities of the layperson to interpret. Their content is most frequently analyzed by clerics who do not question the underlying political or social implications of the text, but use the writing to convey messages to their congregations about how to live a holy existence. In Western society, moreover, what counts as scripture is generally confined to the Judeo-Christian Bible, leaving the voices of minorities, as well as the holy texts of faiths from Africa and Asia, for example, unheard. In this innovative collection of essays that aims to turn the traditional bible-study definition of scriptures on its head, Vincent L. Wimbush leads an in-depth look at the social, cultural, and racial meanings invested in these texts. Contributors hail from a wide array of academic fields and geographic locations and include such noted academics as Susan Harding, Elisabeth Shüssler Fiorenza, and William L. Andrews. Purposefully transgressing disciplinary boundaries, this ambitious book opens the door to different interpretations and critical orientations, and in doing so, allows an ultimately humanist definition of scriptures to emerge.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aSacred booksxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aWimbush, Vincent, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813544625423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813544625.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK